4. Annotation Guidelines

4.1  Norm Compliance Score (NCₜ)
The norm compliance score per turn is computed per Equation 9 of the paper as:
NCₜ = cos( v(aₜ), v*(pₜ) )  +  μ₁ · σ(turnₜ; τ)  +  μ₂ · 𝐼ₖ[ I_constraintₖ(aₜ) ]

•  v(aₜ) is the behaviour vector of the agent’s chosen action (lexical, prosodic, kinesic descriptors)
•  v*(pₜ) is the gold behaviour vector of the active SPT social practice
•  The second term σ measures timing alignment with the practice’s expected turn structure
•  The third term averages satisfaction of hard normative constraints over all active constraints k
In the synthetic datasets, NC scores were assigned by human annotators using a standardised rubric developed from the SPT practice library.

4.2  Emotion Labels
Base emotion labels follow the 6-class CMU-MOSEI scheme for cross-dataset compatibility: neutral, happy, sad, angry, surprised, disgusted. For the conflict mediation dataset, three additional classes were introduced to capture de-escalation dynamics not represented in standard affect corpora:

Additional Class	Definition	Scenario
defensive	Speaker is resisting perceived blame or accusation	Mediation
anxious	Speaker shows worry or uncertainty without clear anger	Mediation
calm	Speaker has moved to a composed, non-reactive emotional state	Mediation

4.3  SPT Practice Library
Each practice_active value in the dataset maps to a formal Social Practice Theory tuple defined in Section 3 of the paper (Equation 6):
p = ⟨ pre(p),  acts(p),  post(p),  mean(p) ⟩

•  pre(p) — preconditions that must hold over task context and user affect
•  acts(p) — action schematic with timing and turn-taking constraints
•  post(p) — expected effects on user state and interaction progress
•  mean(p) — cultural meaning encoding (politeness level, deference, formality)
The full practice library with all tuples for all three scenarios is implemented in src/compliance/practice_library.py in the repository.

